    "summary": "The Middle Assyrian Empire, spanning approximately 1392 to 1077 BC, represented the first phase of significant Assyrian imperial expansion and established the administrative and military traditions that would later flower into the Neo-Assyrian Empire of the Iron Age. Beginning with the reign of Ashur-uballit I, who elevated Assyria from a vassal of the Mitanni kingdom to an independent power, Middle Assyrian kings steadily extended their control across northern Mesopotamia.\n\nThe Middle Assyrian period reached its peak under Tukulti-Ninurta I (r. c. 1243–1207 BC), who extended Assyrian rule to its greatest territorial extent, conquered the [[event:1829|Kassite]] capital of Babylon around 1225 BC — an event commemorated in the Tukulti-Ninurta Epic — and controlled territories from the upper Euphrates to the Persian Gulf. This was the first Assyrian conquest of Babylon, establishing a pattern that would be repeated several times over the following centuries.\n\nMiddle Assyrian law and administration were highly developed. The Middle Assyrian Laws, preserved on clay tablets, represent one of the most extensive surviving law codes of the ancient Near East, revealing a society with strict regulations governing property, women's status, and sexual conduct. Assyrian scribes produced sophisticated administrative records and the king maintained a system of provincial governors and garrisons to control conquered territories.\n\nThe Middle Assyrian state contracted in the decades around 1200 BC under pressure from the [[event:1815|Bronze Age Collapse]] and migrations of Aramaean nomads who disrupted agricultural regions. The empire shrank back toward its Assyrian heartland, though it survived and gradually rebuilt power over subsequent centuries, eventually reemerging as the Neo-Assyrian Empire from the tenth century BC onward.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Assyrian_Empire",
